The city, through its location on the River Ouse and its proximity to the Great North Road became a major trading centre. King John granted the city's first charter in 1212,Charter Day celebrations for York announced confirming trading rights in England and Europe. York became a major cloth manufacturing and trading centre. Edward I further stimulated the city's economy by using the city as a base for his war in Scotland.  The city was the location of significant unrest during the so-called Peasants' Revolt in 1381.  The city acquired an increasing degree of autonomy from central government including the privileges granted by a charter of Richard II in 1396.